sues—such as climate change, environmental destruction, and resource management—from a diverse range of perspectives. With a kind of foreboding, it asks what the world was like, and will be like, without us, whether we are negligible and the universe random, whether nature can truly be explained, whether it is good or evil, or whether nature is simply a thought we think. This is a profoundly unique work, a thrillingly interdisciplinary piece of scholarly literature that probes the mysteries of nature and humans alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNatural disasters. 0aNatural lawxPhilosophy. 0aNatural law-Philosophy. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  atunguska event, siberia, explosion, woodland, nature, forest, mystery, unexplained, science, meteors, black hole, antimatter, physics, alfred north whitehead, adolf portmann, paul feyerabend, steven weinberg, gunter hasinger, biology, philosophy, mathematics, understanding, theory, hypothesis, climate change, preservation, conservation, environment, environmentalism, environmental destruction, resource management, natural resources, nonfiction, stewardship, nonhuman animals, wildlife, extinction.1 aWinkler, Michael.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226174006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226174006/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles